04322nam a22006495i 9781646020386DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97816460203867 a10.1515/97816460203862doi  a(DE-B1597)584579  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPJ4150b.M33 2019 7aREL1140002bisacsh04a492/.670142231 aMcAffee, Matthew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLife and Mortality in Ugaritic :bA Lexical and Literary Study /cMatthew McAffee. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (392 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aExplorations in Ancient Near Eastern Civilizations ;v700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. An Analysis of Words for "Life" in Ugaritic -- tChapter 2. NPŠ and Other Terms for Body Parts Especially Associated with the Concept of Life -- tChapter 3. An Analysis of Words for "Death" in Ugaritic -- tChapter 4. The Ugaritic Rapaʾūma -- tChapter 5. Life and Mortality at Ugarit: A Synthesis -- tAppendix. First Millennium BC Funerary Monuments -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Scripture -- tIndex of Ugaritic Sources -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile topics such as death, funerary cult, and the netherworld have received considerable scholarly attention in the context of the Ugaritic textual corpus, the related concept of life has been relatively neglected. Life and Mortality in Ugaritic takes as its premise that one cannot grasp the significance of mwt ("to die") without first having wrestled with the concept of ḥyy ("to live"). In this book, Matthew McAffee takes a lexical approach to the study of life and death in the Ugaritic textual corpus. He identifies and analyzes the Ugaritic terms most commonly used to talk about life and mortality in order to construct a more representative framework of the ancient perspective on these topics, and he concludes by synthesizing the results of this lexical study into a broader literary discussion that considers, among other things, the implications for our understanding of the first-millennium Katumuwa stele from Zincirli.McAffee's study complements previous scholarly work in this area, which has tended to rely on conceptual and theoretical treatment of mortality, and advances the discussion by providing a more focused lexical analysis of the Ugaritic terms in question. It will be of interest to Semitic scholars and those who study Ugaritic in particular, in addition to students of the culture of the ancient Levant.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDeathxTerminology. 0aLifexTerminology. 0aUgaritic languagexLexicology. 7aRELIGION / Ancient.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074520740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781646020386zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781646020386423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781646020386.jpg  a978-3-11-074520-7  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK